I created this chart on a whim. It's based my own aesthetics and surely very
biased. If you are curious about my criteria, you can check out Piero Scaruf's
website scaruf.com. Once a friend told me that my way to approach aesthetics
in music is quite similar to Scarufs. I checked his website, and I actually agreed
to at least 60% of his stuff. The major difference is that Im more technical driven
in assessing rock music, or at least guitar players. Scaruf also published a list of
best rock guitarists of all time https://www.scaruf.com/music/guitar.html. I
found some parts quite intriguing. Yet it seemed that Scaruf, with a deeper
root in jazz and classics, hadn't paid enough attention to rock guitar music,
especially the footage of some rare live performances (Theres no list of all-time
best rock performances on his website. Its understandable since the internet
didnt prevail in the last century.).
Brief interpretation of each quadrant:
Up: Graceful
Down: Cringe
Left: slow hands. Since some players are more rhythm-driven, this could be
also be righteously misinterpreted as non-shredders.
Right: shredders
Red Quadrant: LESS IS MORE, ingenuity, artsy.
Blue Quadrants: MORE IS MORE, virtuosity, craftsmanship, discipline.
Green Quadrant: LESS IS LESS, boring or simply unqualied as a professional
(harsh).
Purple Quadrant: MORE IS LESS, bullshitting, some not aware of their
tawdriness, some just technocrats.
A players inuence or achievements is not a major criterion to assess his level of
grace. Instead, it largely comes from a purely aesthetic perspective. It is
denitely possible for a cringe player to exert a major inuence on a graceful
player. Wise players can synthesise and rene what they were fed with. If you
tend to assess an artist by the sales of their artworks or popularity, my website
might be a hostile place for you.
Due to the limitation of space, many other guitarists that one idolises or loathes
might not be included. Some excellent guitar players like Dave Mustaine, James
Heteld, and Billy Corgan are mainly in charge of rhythm and songwriting in
their groups. Id rather not include them in this chart, since it primarily aims to
assess lead players or guitarists with a regular solo career. It will be better to
evaluate those rhythm and songwriting geniuses with another chart. On the
perfect centrist point lie Page and SRV, whose names are blurred by the axis.
Don take this chart seriously, peace.

Appendix IV: Top 50 Rock Guitar Solos of All Time (live,
record, or in other forms)
Something in the Water - Prince (1984-1985, sound check)[Thanks God, the sound checks
were recorded. With no need to please the audience, no desire for prot, and zero stage
fright, Prince let the best solo on earth ow. Prince didnt nd the music. Music found Prince.
Its beyond expression. Its natural.]
Final Jam Chorzw - John Frusciante (2007, RHCP live in Chorzw, Poland
https://youtu.be/eo6KxjmE_BY?si=D-7DjVxsE2UP0DMo)[An autograph and biography of
John Frusciante. No one else can unfold such a tangible miniature of their own musical and
spiritual life in 13 minutes.]
1988 Jam - TJ Helmerich (1988, video record uploaded by himself
https://youtu.be/C0vxPJFnxCo?si=2JiSUiWVwIo-Lwri)[The solo was way ahead of its
time. TJ started the second tapping revolution here. He showed the modern chav kids how
technical a proto-indie rock track could be while maintaining sentimental depth: euphoric
bloom and futuristic nostalgia at the same time.]
Maggot Brain - Eddie Hazel (1971, title song in the album by Funkadelic)[Unfathomed
depth. Read the preface of Revolt Against the Modern Word by Julius Evola. Otherwise, youll
never understand the speech before the solo. If you dont understand the speech, you are not
going to feel the solo. Sublime tradition. Hats off.]
Hectors House - Allan Holdsworth(1972, featured in Ian Carrs Belladonna)[Young
Holdsworths anarchist orgy]
